        "### 2.4b: Apply Skin-Context Constraints\n",
        "\n",
        "To account for the physiological impact of skin pH on keratinocyte metabolism, the lower bound of the proton exchange reaction (MAR09048) was constrained to reflect the electrochemical gradient. In the High SA condition (pH 6.13), the bound was left unconstrained (-1000 mmol/gDW/h) to reflect a favorable export gradient. In the Low SA condition (pH 5.13), the bound was restricted to -400 mmol/gDW/h to simulate the thermodynamic resistance (back-pressure) exerted by the more acidic extracellular environment.\n",
        "\n",
        "The \"Open\" State (-1000) is the standard \"unconstrained\" value in COBRA models. At pH 6.13 (High SA), the concentration of H\n",
        "+\n",
        "  outside the cell is relatively low. This creates a \"favorable\" gradient, meaning the cell can dump protons as fast as its enzymes can work.\n",
        "\n",
        "The \"Restricted\" State (-400): At pH 5.13 (Low SA), the external concentration of protons is 10 times higher (10\n",
        "−5.13\n",
        "  vs 10\n",
        "−6.13\n",
        " ). This creates \"back-pressure.\"\n",
        "\n",
        " scale the bound linearly or logarithmically with the pH difference:\n",
        "![Screenshot 2026-05-15 at 14.35.50.png](data:image/png;base64,)\n",
        "\n",
        "By reducing the bound from -1000 to -400, we are simulating a 60% increase in resistance to proton export caused by the more acidic environment of \"Healthy/Low SA\" skin.\n"
      ]
    },
